2. Question: An electrical manufacturing company¶

An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions.

solution: the given problem follows binomial distribution

In [3]:
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats
n=10
p=0.05
k=np.arange(0,11)
binomial = stats.binom.pmf(k,n,p)
binomial

# 2.A Probability that none of the items are defective?
print(f'''Probability that none of the items are defective are {round(binomial[0],4)}''')

3. Question: A car salesman sells on an average 3 cars per week¶

answers: A. Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars = 0.9502 B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars = 0.6161 C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold per week.

In [8]:
rate = 3
n= np.arange(0,12)
poisson = stats.poisson.pmf(n,rate)
#3.A. #probability of selling some car = 1- probability of selling no car
P1 = 1-poisson[0]
print(f'''probability of selling some car is {round(P1,4)}''')

probability of selling some car is 0.9502
In [9]:
#3.B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars
P2 =round(poisson[2]+poisson[3]+poisson[4],4)
print(f'''Probability of selling more than 2 but less than 5 cars are {P2}''')

Probability of selling more than 2 but less than 5 cars are 0.6161
In [10]:
#3.C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold per week.
poisson_cum = stats.poisson.cdf(n,rate)
poisson_cum
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(n,poisson_cum, 'o-')
plt.title('Poisson\'s cumulative distribution')
plt.xlabel('number of cars')
plt.ylabel('cumulative probability of cars')
plt.show()

4. Question:¶

Accuracy in understanding orders for a speech based bot at a restaurant is important for the Company X which has designed, marketed and launched the product for a contactless delivery due to the COVID-19 pandemic. Recognition accuracy that measures the percentage of orders that are taken correctly is 86.8%. Suppose that you place order with the bot and two friends of yours independently place orders with the same bot. Answer the following questions. A. What is the probability that all three orders will be recognised correctly? B. What is the probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly? C. What is the probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly?

In [11]:
#solution: the given problem follows binomial distribution
k   =  np.arange(0,4)
p   =  0.868
n   =  3
binomial = stats.binom.pmf(k,n,p)
binomial

probability that all three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.654
In [13]:
# 4.B  probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly =P2

 probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.0023
In [14]:
# 4.C  probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly =P3
binom_cum = stats.binom.cdf(k,n,p)
P3 = 1-round(binom_cum[1],4)
print( f'''probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly is {P3}''')

probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.9523
Answers: 4.A. probability that all three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.654 4.B. probability that none of the three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.0023 4.C. probability that at least two of the three orders will be recognised correctly is 0.9523

5. Question:¶

A group of 300 professionals sat for a competitive exam. The results show the information of marks obtained by them have a mean of 60 and a standard deviation of 12. The pattern of marks follows a normal distribution. Answer the following questions. A. What is the percentage of students who score more than 80. B. What is the percentage of students who score less than 50. C. What should be the distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction?

In [15]:
# 5.A percentage of students who score more than 80
n= 300
mu = 60
sd = 12
In [16]:
# 5.A percentage of students who score more than 80 
x1 = 80
z = (x1-mu)/sd
P = 1 - stats.norm.cdf(z)
print(f'''percentage of students who score more than 80 is {round(P,4)*100} %''')

percentage of students who score more than 80 is 4.78 %
In [17]:
# 5.B.percentage of students who score less than 50
x2 = 50
z1 = (x2-mu)/sd
z1
P1 = stats.norm.cdf(z1)
print(f'''percentage of students who score less than 50 is {round(P1,4)*100} %''')

percentage of students who score less than 50 is 20.23 %
# 5.C. Distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction the top 10% of the students, corresponds to (100-10)% it is 90 marks. The Z score corresponds to 90(to the upper tail side from the mean) from standard normal distribution table is 1.282 P[Z>=(x3-mu)/sd] =0.1 (x3 - mu)/sd = 1.282 x3 = 75.384 distinction marks is 75Answers: 5.A. percentage of students who score more than 80 is 4.78 % 5.B. percentage of students who score less than 50 is 20.23 % 5.C. distinction marks is 75

6. Question:¶

Explain 1 real life industry scenario other than the ones mentioned above where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied statistics to get a data driven business solution.

In this dataset example we will discuss the main methods in action by analyzing a dataset on the churn rate of telecom operator clients. The objective of the study is to predict that a customer is not loyal (Churn=1) in the case when the number of calls to the service center is greater than 3 and the International Plan is added (and predicting Churn=0 otherwise) 1. The first step is data reading and exploration. Using python libraries of Numpy,Pandas the dataset can be cleaned and visualized and later hypothetical can be made on the dataset to analyze the dataset. Pandas is a Python library that provides extensive means for data analysis. Data scientists often work with data stored in table formats like .csv, .tsv, or .xlsx. Pandas makes it very convenient to load, process, and analyze such tabular data using SQL-like queries. In conjunction with Matplotlib and Seaborn, Pandas provides a wide range of opportunities for visual analysis of tabular data.The main data structures in Pandas are implemented with Series and DataFrame classes. The former is a one-dimensional indexed array of some fixed data type. The latter is a two-dimensional data structure - a table - where each column contains data of the same type. You can see it as a dictionary of Series instances. DataFrames are great for representing real data: rows correspond to instances (examples, observations, etc.), and columns correspond to features of these instances. 2. Reading CSV file 3. Detecting the size and shape of the dataset using .columns,.shape,.info commands. 4. Analysing datatype of the attributes. 5. To do statistics with the exploration of describe command. 6. Indexing and retrieving data 7.Determining What are average values of numerical features for churned users? 8. Determining How much time (on average) do churned users spend on the phone during daytime? 9. Determining What is the maximum length of international calls among loyal users (Churn == 0) who do not have an international plan? 10.Grouping, using contingency table to see how the observations in our sample are distributed in the context of two variables. 11.First attempt at predicting telecom churn is related to the International plan feature using a crosstab contingency table and also through visual analysis to be made by using matplotlib and seaborn. 12. After doing detailed analysis without using machinelearning models these conclusion can be drawn: i) Predicting that a customer is not loyal (Churn=1) in the case when the number of calls to the service center is greater than 3 and the International Plan is added (and predicting Churn=0 otherwise), we might expect an accuracy of 85.8% (we are mistaken only 464 + 9 times). This number, 85.8%, that we got through this very simple reasoning serves as a good starting point (baseline) for the further machine learning models that we will build. ii) The share of loyal clients in the sample is 85.5%. The most naive model that always predicts a "loyal customer" on such data will guess right in about 85.5% of all cases. That is, the proportion of correct answers (accuracy) of subsequent models should be no less than this number, and will hopefully be significantly higher; With the help of a simple forecast that can be expressed by the following formula: "International plan = True & Customer Service calls > 3 => Churn = 1, else Churn = 0", we can expect a guessing rate of 85.8%, which is just above 85.5%.

# simple program to remove 'K' and 'M' from the column and multiply with the corresponding values.
def value_to_float(x):
    if type(x) == float or type(x) == int:                  # defining a function to convert the values in 'K','M' and
                                                           # 'B' to its respective values
        return x
    if 'K' in x:
        if len(x) > 1:
            return float(x.replace('K', '')) * 1000
        return 1000.0
    if 'M' in x:
        if len(x) > 1:
            return float(x.replace('M', '')) * 1000000
        return 1000000.0
    if 'B' in x:
        return float(x.replace('B', '')) * 1000000000
    return 0.0

df['Funding in $'] = df['Funding in $'].apply(value_to_float)

def convert_fund_value(y):
    if type(y) == float or type(y) == int:                  # defining a function to convert the values in 'K','M' and
                                                           # 'B' to its respective values
        return y
    if 'K' in y:
        if len(y) > 1:
            return float(y.replace('K', '')) * 1000
        return 1000.0
    if 'M' in y:
        if len(y) > 1:
            return float(y.replace('M', '')) * 1000000
        return 1000000.0
    if 'B' in y:
        return float(y.replace('B', '')) * 1000000000
    return 0.0

Step 2: Decide the significance level Here we select α = 0.05 Step 3: Identify the test statistic Here we have three groups. Analysis of variance can determine whether the means of three or more groups are different. ANOVA uses F-tests to statistically test the equality of means. Step 4: Calculate p value using ANOVA table statsmodels.formula.api.ols creates a model from a formula and dataframe statsmodels.api.sm.stats.anova_lm gives an Anova table for one or more fitted linear models.

Write your observations¶

on improvements or suggestions on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected to perform a better data analysis.

Based on the analysis of the dataset interms of visualization and statistics analysis the following points can be included: 1.Lot of missing values were present in the dataframe especially in the fund raised by the company (214) followed by company's product(6). The missing values can be avoided by effective analysing of dataset. 2.Data regarding feasibility study and social impact of the product made by the company is missing as it is the one of the main criteria for deciding the result of the event. 3.Funds raised across different events could be more precise and fine tuned. 4. Events conducted can also be fine tuned with respect to cities or country where it was conducted, and the year when it was conducted by creating seperate attributes for the same. 5. Results of the events can also be made with seperate attributes indicating 'Winner', 'Runner-Up' and so on. 6. Volume (how many) and information about the companies participated for the event on the particular year and its close competators could be included as a seperate attributes for effective analysis.
